  "notes_normalized": "Cannabis is legal in Michigan under state law for recreational adult use. Medical cannabis is also legal under a regulated state program in Michigan. Cannabis remains federally illegal in United States. Possession is limited to varies (see official sources).",
  "notes_raw": "style=\"background:#196E92;\" | {{Hs|1}} Before cannabis was legalized in the state, possession of any amounts was a misdemeanor offense punishable by up to one year's incarceration and a $2,000 fine, while actual use was punishable by up to 90 days in jail and a $100 fine. If possession was in a public park, the sentence was at most two years and a $2,000 fine. Distributing cannabis without remuneration was a misdemeanor punishable by at most one year in jail and a $1,000 fine. The sale and cultivation of cannabis was a felony punishable by up to 15 years imprisonment and $10,000,000 in fines depending on the number of plants grown and the amount of usable cannabis sold. This is because certain prohibitions remain, for example it is still illegal to consume marijuana as the driver of a car, or smoke it as a passenger. In February 2013, the Supreme Court of Michigan ruled that the 2008 initiative did not allow for the operation of medical cannabis dispensaries in the state.",
